The reason why your code is only updating one list and not both of them is because you are attempting to serialize them ***separately***.

You have taken an ecosystem where one list depends on the other, but you are serializing both lists ***separately***. That&#39;s like cutting a cake in half, storing each half separately, and then trying to put both halves back together later on. That won&#39;t fly.

If you want this to work, you must place ***BOTH*** lists into a single object, and then serialize that object. That is what will allow the relationship to be maintained.

Alternatively, you can try and manually create the relationship yourself, but that would be painful.

As a side note though, I notice that you are using basic Java serialization. Please note that basic Java serialization is a persnickety beast that can cause millions of security holes. Be mindful of that when using it. There are better tools available, rather than just using naked Java serialization.

**EDIT** - To further demonstrate the point, here is an example.

```java
record Child(String name) implements Serializable {}
record Parent(Child one, Child two) implements Serializable {}

Child child = new Child(&quot;Charles&quot;);
Parent parent = new Parent(child, child);

try (FileOutputStream fileOutputStream = new FileOutputStream(&quot;out&quot;)) 
{

    var objectOutputStream = new ObjectOutputStream(fileOutputStream); 
        
    objectOutputStream.writeObject(parent);

    objectOutputStream.close();

}

catch (IOException e) 
{

    throw new RuntimeException(e);

}

try (
        var fileInputStream = new FileInputStream(&quot;out&quot;);
        var objectInputStream = new ObjectInputStream(fileInputStream)
)
{
        
    Parent idk = (Parent) objectInputStream.readObject();
    System.out.println(idk);
    System.out.println(idk.one() == idk.two());
        
    objectInputStream.close();
    fileInputStream.close();

}

catch (Exception e)
{

        throw new RuntimeException(e);

}
```

